        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Turbulence and hemolysis model selection must be justified by benchmark evidence. Model form uncertainty must be estimated by comparison with at least one alternative model formulation, and the impact on the decision QoI must be bounded."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Blood rheological parameters (viscosity, density) sourced from literature with documented uncertainty distributions. Power-law hemolysis model coefficients (C, alpha, beta) carry explicitly low confidence (CV=14% on C) due to limited experimental calibration data in the literature; this is the dominant uncertainty source identified in the Monte Carlo UQ. The gap is honestly documented: sensitivity analysis confirms that even at the 90th-percentile upper bound of C, predicted NIH remains 31% below the clinical acceptance threshold, providing adequate margin. No attempt is made to obscure or minimize this uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/modelinputs-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All uncertain model inputs must have documented probability distributions with traceable sources. Dominant uncertainty contributors must be identified via sensitivity analysis. Decision margin must be demonstrated sufficient to absorb input uncertainty at the 90th percentile."
      }
